column1: #Summary1=(human1) This dictionary entry for the word 'next' gives its dialectal forms, etymology as a superlative of 'near' from Middle and Old English nexte and nīehsta from Proto-Germanic *nēhwist, its cognates (e.g. Dutch naast, Danish næste), pronunciation /nεkst/ and related synonyms and antonyms, accompanied by usage examples as an adjective, determiner, adverb, preposition and noun.

#Summary2=(claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022) This dictionary entry details the word 'next', tracing its etymology from Middle English 'nexte' and Old English 'nīehsta', providing pronunciations, and defining its usage as an adjective, determiner, adverb, preposition, and noun to indicate proximity in space, time, or sequence.

#Summary3=(gpt4o) This dictionary entry explores the word 'next', detailing alternative forms like 'neest' and 'neist', etymology from Middle English and Proto-Germanic roots, cognates in various languages, pronunciation as /nɛkst/, definitions and usage as an adjective, determiner, adverb, preposition, and noun, along with examples, synonyms, and antonyms.

#Summary4=(Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct; postedited) This dictionary entry for the word "next" provides its etymology, synonyms, antonyms, usage examples, and definitions as an adjective, determiner, adverb, preposition, and noun with various senses in time, sequence, and spatial relationships.

#Summary5=(Qwen2.5-3B-Instruct) The document defines and explains the English word "next," providing etymology, pronunciations, definitions, usage examples, and related concepts, while also discussing its comparative forms and obsolete or poetic uses.

#Text=From Middle English nexte , nexste , nixte , from Old English nīehsta , nīehste , etc. , inflected forms of nīehst ( “ nearest , next ” ) , superlative form of nēah ( “ nigh , near ” ) , corresponding to Proto-Germanic *nēhwist ( “ nearest , closest ” ) ; equivalent to nigh + -est .

#Text=Cognate with Saterland Frisian naist ( “ next ” ) , Dutch naast ( “ next ” ) , German nächst ( “ next ” ) , Danish næste ( “ next ” ) , Swedish näst ( “ next ” ) , Icelandic næst ( “ next ” ) , Persian نزد ( nazd , “ near , with ” ) .
#Text=Nearest in place or position , having nothing similar intervening ; adjoining .
#Text=The man in the next bunk kept me awake all night with his snoring .
#Text=She lives a mile or two away , in the next village .
#Text=( obsolete ) Most direct , or shortest or nearest in distance or time .
#Text=Nearest in order , succession , or rank ; immediately following ( or sometimes preceding ) in order .
#Text=On Wednesday next , I 'm going to Spain .
#Text=the next chapter ; the next week ; the Sunday next before Easter
#Text=The man was driven by his love for money and his desire to become the next Bill Gates .
#Text=Near was originally the comparative form of nigh ; the superlative form was next .
#Text=Nigh is used today mostly in archaic , poetic , or regional contexts .
#Text=( nearest in order ) : See also Thesaurus : former or Thesaurus : subsequent
#Text=Denotes the one immediately following the current or most recent one .
#Text=Next week would be a good time to meet .

#Text=( of days of the week or months of the year ) Closest in the future , or closest but one if the closest is very soon ; of days , sometimes thought to specifically refer to the instance closest to seven days ( one week ) in the future .
#Text=The party is next Tuesday ; that is , not tomorrow , but eight days from now .
#Text=When you say next Thursday , do you mean Thursday this week or Thursday next week ?
#Text=In a time , place , rank or sequence closest or following .
#Text=They live in the next closest house .
#Text=It 's the next best thing to ice cream .
#Text=( conjunctive ) So as to follow in time or sequence something previously mentioned .
#Text=First we removed all the handles ; next , we stripped off the old paint .
#Text=When we next meet , you 'll be married .
#Text=( obsolete or poetic ) On the side of ; nearest or adjacent to ; next to .
#Text=The one that follows after this one .
#Text=Next , please , do n't hold up the queue !
#Text=One moment she was there , the next she was n't .
